description:
While overseeing alteration works at a house, Mr Koh Kok Heng, 53, fell through a floor opening and landed on a staircase about 4.7m below.

His sons rushed to the hospital when they heard the news, but by the time they arrived, it was too late. Their father had already died.

MOM said that the accident is the fourth fatal workplace incident here since the start of February.

description:
Useful information, as you spring-clean for CNY2021. 

Here are some places in Singapore where you can donate your pre-loved items:

#1: Pass-It-On
Pass-It-On connects the people with items to donate to the folks who need them, via its online platform.
How to donate: Keep an eye out for requests at www.passiton.org.sg.

#2: SG Mummies United
Set up during the circuit breaker last year, this Facebook group is a blessings community that aims to help mothers who may be struggling to make ends meet.
How to donate: Join the Facebook group at https://www.facebook.com/groups/sgmummiesunited/.

#3: Greensquare 
Greensquare collects recyclable textiles. 
How to donate: Drop off pre-loved items at over 50 locations islandwide. If you have more than 15kg worth of items (approximately three full large black trash bags), Greensquare will pick them up at your doorstep for free â€” just schedule an appointment on their website (below). More info at https://www.greensquare.com.sg/.

For more details and more options, click on the link in bio @todayonline 

#prelovedsingapore #preloved #sgdonate #donate #wheretodonate

description:
A real story about fake news. 

More than two-thirds of Singaporeans are unable to discern between real and fake news, especially seniors and those living in smaller public flats. This is one of the findings from a study released by the Institute of Policy Studies (IPS) earlier this month.

The studyâ€™s authors, who interviewed 2,011 respondents face-to-face between Nov 1 and Dec 31 last year, looked into how susceptible Singaporeans are to false information.

To measure this, respondents were shown a manipulated news article â€” fake news â€” and asked to determine its trustworthiness. Only 32.5 per cent of respondents correctly said that the article was not trustworthy.

The rest believed its contents to various degrees â€” 27 per cent said that it was somewhat trustworthy, and 40.6 per cent graded it as either trustworthy or very trustworthy.

In a media briefing, the two IPS researchers, senior research fellow Carol Soon and research assistant Shawn Goh, said the study showed that a personâ€™s susceptibility to fake news was related to several demographic, socio-economic and psychological factors...

Read on, when you click on the link in bio @todayonline

description:
â€œStripped of all the bells and tinkles, it is perhaps a blessingâ€ for Christians as the quieter celebrations provide them with a chance to reflect on the true meaning of Christmas, said a spokesperson for the archbishop's communications office at the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Singapore.

â€œWe are also encouraged to reflect on the first Christmas, where Christ was born without fanfare and only the angels and the shepherds, along with their sheep, bore witness to his birth.â€

As Christians get ready to celebrate the birth of Jesus Christ today, the familiar hymns and carols that would typically resonate through church halls during Christmas festivities will be largely heard online due to the ongoing Covid-19 pandemic.

The various churches interviewed by TODAY said that while they have gradually raised the limits of the number of worshippers allowed within their premises, in accordance with government guidelines, there are some people who are more comfortable worshipping from home because of the global health crisis.

Religious organisations have been allowed to admit up to 100 people since Oct 3 â€” with safe distancing and management measures in place. This limit is due to be raised to 250 people, in five zones of up to 50 people each, when Singapore enters the final phase of reopening its economy on Dec 28.

Read on, when you click on the link in bio @todayonline

description:
The Heavenly King is 55. 

Earlier this week, Kwok, who has COVID-19 to thank for this lull in his usually back-breaking work schedule, posted a photo with his wife Moka Fang and their two daughters, Chantelle, three, and Charlotte, one, along with an emotional note to his fans. 

â€œEvery year on October 26, I receive blessings from my family, colleagues, friends and fans from all over the world. I always feel thankful and consider myself very blessed because of all the well-wishes,â€ he wrote.

He added that in the past, he would always be at work on his birthday. 

This year, however, he continued: "I just finished filming my movie and could take a short break from work on my birthday. I had a small celebration with my colleagues and my family because of safe distancing rules. It was a simple party."

Fans were delighted to see a photo of Kwok's family together, as the star rarely posts photos of his two daughters. The photo, which showed the three women in his life giving him a kiss, quickly went viral online. 

More happy snaps and details, when you click on the link in bio @todayonline 

Photos: PBE Media

Earlier this week, Kwok, who has COVID-19 to thank for this lull in his usually back-breaking work schedule, posted a photo with his wife Moka Fang and their two daughters, Chantelle, three, and Charlotte, one, along with an emotional note to his fans. 

â€œEvery year on October 26, I receive blessings from my family, colleagues, friends and fans from all over the world. I always feel thankful and consider myself very blessed because of all the well-wishes,â€ he wrote.

He added that in the past, he would always be at work on his birthday. 

This year, however, he continued: "I just finished filming my movie and could take a short break from work on my birthday. I had a small celebration with my colleagues and my family because of safe distancing rules. It was a simple party."

Fans were delighted to see a photo of Kwok's family together, as the star rarely posts photos of his two daughters. The photo, which showed the three women in his life giving him a kiss, quickly went viral online. 

More happy snaps and details, when you click on the link in bio @todayonline 

Photos: PBE Media 

#aaronkwok #heavenlyking #birthday #family

description:
Interactions with family members of patients are a common part of Ms Cerene Wong's work. She is a medical social worker at Changi General Hospitalâ€™s critical care units.

But in this Covid-19 climate, how she delivers care to patients has had to be done differently.

While she used to be able to comfort anxious families by using a soothing tone of voice and non-verbal cues such as hugs or facial expressions, she has to now convey comfort and empathy from behind a mask. Touch has also been minimised because of safe distancing. 

It is even more challenging for the loved ones of Covid-19 patients. 

Before the coronavirus emerged, family members could talk to patients, sponge their faces, hands and legs, and even lighten the atmosphere in the room with songs.

But now, they cannot touch their loved ones to comfort and reassure them. Families may also be in a dilemma, with fears of their own safety and health conflicting with concerns about their loved ones.

Read on, when you click on the link in bio @todayonline 

Photo: Changi General Hospital @cghsg

description:
âœˆï¸ It was his life-long dream to be a pilot but for Steven (not his real name), his career was over before it even began.

He is among the cadet pilots from the Singapore Airlines (SIA) Group who will have to leave the company after completing his third of four phases of training. He never thought his stint would end this way.

Singaporeâ€™s national carrier announced earlier this month that its pilots would be taking 10 to 60 per cent pay cuts, weeks after revealing that it would be retrenching about 2,400 workers across SIA, SilkAir and Scoot.

Since then, some pilots have taken on delivery jobs to make up for lost income. Some are now safe distancing ambassadors. Foreign pilots are returning to their native countries. Some pilots are now studying part-time, while others have had to take loans to keep their children in school. 

Still others have decided to retire early. 

More details, when you click on the link in bio @todayonline

He is among the cadet pilots from the Singapore Airlines (SIA) Group who will have to leave the company after completing his third of four phases of training. He never thought his stint would end this way.

Singaporeâ€™s national carrier announced earlier this month that its pilots would be taking 10 to 60 per cent pay cuts, weeks after revealing that it would be retrenching about 2,400 workers across SIA, SilkAir and Scoot.

Since then, some pilots have taken on delivery jobs to make up for lost income. Some are now safe distancing ambassadors. Foreign pilots are returning to their native countries. Some pilots are now studying part-time, while others have had to take loans to keep their children in school. 

Still others have decided to retire early. 

More details, when you click on the link in bio @todayonline

description:
Youâ€™ve seen plenty of pictures of its exterior, but whatâ€™s it like inside the tech giantâ€™s first store on water in the world?

On the inside, the futuristic-looking circular space is an architectural sight to behold â€” comprising 114 pieces of glass and just 10 vertical mullions for structure. There are no walls inside the light-drenched globular space (just plenty of Apple gadgets and even more space for ample safe distancing). 

Youâ€™ll get 360-degree panoramic views of the waterfront and skyline from wherever you stand on Level 1 of the three-storey retail space.

The Apple store at MBS will open its doors on Sep 10 at 10am, but things will be different from your usual Apple store opening. 

This one's happening in the midst of a pandemic. Entry to the store on opening day will be on an appointment-only basis, and pre-registration is already open on its website (apple.com/sg/marinabaysands).

More details, in the link in bio @todayonline

description:
The Ministry of Health is investigating a family cluster of five cases from two households who had taken part in family gatherings.

The five comprise two female teenagers aged 14 and 17 and three males aged 12, 20 and 21.

They were listed as contacts of "Case 56627", a 13-year-old boy previously described as a community case with no known source of infection.

"These individuals had participated in family gatherings, and investigations are ongoing to see if there were any breaches of safe distancing rules," MOH said.

More details, in the link in bio @todayonline

description:
Clearly, social distancing was out in full force.

Thousands of partygoers packed into a water park over the weekend in the central Chinese city of Wuhan - where the coronavirus first emerged late last year.

The popular Wuhan Maya Beach Water Park was filled with people frolicking in swimsuits and goggles for an electronic music festival. 

Some of the crowd had donned life jackets, but none of the tightly-packed partygoers were seen to be wearing face masks.

More details, in the link in bio @todayonline

description:
Time for your holiday - right here in Singapore. 

Local tours run by operators and tourist guides can now have bigger groups, as long as safe distancing measures are in place between sub-groups of participants, says the Singapore Tourism Board (STB). 

Tours involving transport such as buses can take up to 50 people or at the vehicle's maximum operating capacity after implementation of safe management measures, whichever is lower.

Local walking, cycling and kayaking tours are limited to a maximum of 10 people excluding the tour guide.

Read all the details at #linkinbio

â£â£â£

â£â£â£

â£â£â£
